Program Overview: This program generates a completed 9×9 Sudoku board using a structured mathematical pattern instead of manually entering values. It begins by creating a 2D array to represent the board and an ArrayList containing the numbers 1 through 9 as a base sequence. The program then fills the board row by row using a shifting formula that rearranges the base list in a consistent way for each row. As the program runs, each cell in the 2D array is assigned a value based on this shifting pattern until the entire grid is filled. Once the board is complete, a separate method is used to print the 2D array in a clean, readable format that visually separates the 3×3 sections.

Data Structures: The main thing used to store the Sudoku board is a table with 9 rows and 9 columns. Each little square in the table can hold a number from 1 to 9. As the program runs it fills in the numbers until the whole board is complete. The program also uses a list of numbers from 1 to 9. This list is used to make each line of the board. Of just putting numbers in the program uses this list and moves it around to make different lines. This makes the program more flexible. It does not have to have the answers already.

Algorithm Design: The Sudoku board is made by moving the list of numbers. First the program makes the list of numbers. Then it goes through each line of the board. For each line it calculates how to move the list. This is done with a formula that uses the line number. When it knows how much to move the list it fills in the numbers for that line. It does this by taking numbers from the list. It starts at a different place each time. This means each line is the numbers 1 to 9 in a different order. The program is designed so that the lines, columns and little squares all follow the rules and do not have any numbers twice. In the end the whole board is complete. Is a valid Sudoku puzzle made just using logic.

Methods: The program has two parts. The first part starts the program, makes the table, builds the list of numbers, fills in the board and then prints it out. The printBoard part takes the board and makes it look nice. It adds lines between the rows and columns so it looks like a Sudoku board. This makes it easier to read and understand.
Testing Plan: To make sure the program works it was tested times. First it checked each line to make sure it had the numbers 1 to 9 without any duplicates. Then it checked each column to make sure it was the same. Finally it checked each square to make sure all the numbers were there. The program was run times to make sure it always made a valid Sudoku board. These tests showed that the program works correctly and always makes a board.
